<PROFILE>_AN-EATCKAABFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940120
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JAN 94 / Red tape bill to target hundreds of regulations: Big savings
predicted for industry - Fears over new powers for ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON and DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government yesterday announced a sweeping attack on red tape, aimed at
abolishing or changing 450 items of regulation. Areas covered include shop
opening hours, children in pubs, building society lending and the
streamlining of the law on mergers. There will also be legislation to allow
the contracting out of public services in areas where it is presently
illegal.
Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, said the de-regulation
and contracting out bill was 'the biggest bonfire of controls that has taken
place in modern times in this country'. It would save industry 'hundreds of
millions of pounds, at a very modest assumption', he said.
At Westminster, the bill was immediately attacked because of the powers it
would give ministers to amend or repeal laws without primary legislation.
Downing Street officials admitted the measure - originally flagged as an
important part of a legislative programme designed to unite the Conservative
party - would be 'a difficult bill to get through'. But they said the prime
minister was confident of the government's ability to do so.
The bill contains a requirement for ministers to wait 40 days between laying
a draft order before parliament and submitting a final draft for
parliamentary debate. The government said this interim period would allow
for additional parliamentary scrutiny. It suggested that new scrutiny
committees could be established in the Commons and the Lords to perform this
task.
Mr Heseltine said there were 55 pieces of legislation that would be
appropriate for the use of the new powers. A further 22 would need primary
legislation. He said: 'This is the first stage of a deregulation initiative.
It is very important to recognise there will be subsequent stages.'
Mr Francis Maude, a junior Foreign Office minister before losing his seat at
the last election, has been appointed head of a de-regulation taskforce to
carry the programme forward.
Mr Heseltine said the measures were intended to increase the competitiveness
of UK industry. Government departments introducing legislation would have to
consult two or three typical small firms about its effect.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry spokesman, said 'ministers must not
be allowed to smuggle in lower standards under the cloak of cutting red
tape'.
Analysis and reaction, Page 9
Editorial Comment, Page 19
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
              DRIVE TO DE-REGULATE: KEY AREAS OF CHANGE
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
The law prohibiting shops from staying open late at night is to be
scrapped.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Children under 14 are to be allowed into pubs, subject to certain
conditions.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Building societies are to be allowed to lend on the security of
property owned by third parties, such as a parent's home.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Competition law is to be changed, streamlining the process by which
mergers can be agreed with the authorities.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
The contracting out of certain public services, such as the
administration of civil service pension schemes, is to be made legal.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
