<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Chrysler results help sustain
Dow at record
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
US stocks were little changed in largely featureless trading yesterday, but
with the market gaining support from stable bond prices and some better than
expected fourth-quarter results, writes Martin Dickson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average ended unchanged at 3,870.29, although
maintaining Monday's record close. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 edged up 0.95
to 474.25 and the Nasdaq composite gained 0.84 at 793.02. NYSE volume was
fairly heavy at 309.7m shares and advances outscored falls by 1,198 to 892.
Apart from a dip at the opening, the Dow spent the day in positive
territory, at one time gaining nearly 10 points, but gave up the advance
towards the close.
Sentiment was helped in the morning by stronger than expected results from
Chrysler, the car manufacturer, which reported fourth-quarter earnings per
share of Dollars 2.11, compared to forecasts of around Dollars 1.60.
Chrysler closed Dollars  3/4 higher at Dollars 62 1/2 and the figures buoyed
the rest of the automobile sector, General Motors adding Dollars 1 3/8 at
Dollars 62 1/8 and Ford Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 68 5/8 .
A large number of money centre and super-regional banks also reported
yesterday, and their figures were generally ahead of expectation and showed
a strong improvement in asset quality. However, share prices mostly dipped
on profit-taking. Wells Fargo lost Dollars 2 3/8 at Dollars 133 3/4 ,
Nationsbank Dollars  1/2 at Dollars 49 1/4 , Chemical Banking Dollars 1 at
Dollars 40 1/2 and Citicorp Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 40 7/8 , but Chase
Manhattan firmed Dollars  1/4 to Dollars 35 3/4 .
Trading was also enlivened by a revised takeover bid for Paramount
Communications from Viacom, which slightly raised the cash it is offering
for 50.1 per cent of the company and also improved features of the
securities it is offering for the remaining 49.9 per cent.
Analysts said the new terms appeared to make its bid competitive with the
higher offer on the table from QVC Network and was likely to keep the
takeover battle alive until the February 1 date set by Paramount for final
offers.
Viacom's non-voting 'B' shares, which form the major part of its package of
securities, fell Dollars 1 3/8 to Dollars 37 3/4 , while QVC dipped Dollars
 1/2 to Dollars 43. Paramount rose Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars 80. Blockbuster
Entertainment, which has agreed to be acquired by Viacom as part of the
Paramount bid, held at Dollars 28.
Drugs group Eli Lilly advanced Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 61 5/8 after
announcing plans to divest its medical device and diagnostics businesses and
take Dollars 1.2bn of restructuring and other charges in the fourth quarter.
Controls group Honeywell shed Dollars  7/8 to Dollars 32 3/4 after reporting
fourth-quarter earnings of 85 cents a share, up from 79 cents, while
Grumman, the defence group, rose Dollars  3/4 to Dollars 42 5/8 on
announcing plans to cut operating costs by nearly Dollars 600m over the next
three years.
Canada
Toronto rose afresh to set another record high. The TSE 300 index ended 17.7
up at 4,561.9 as rises led declines by 444 to 369 after volume of 73.5m
shares. Financial services remained strong, adding 1.14 per cent at 3,553.1.
</TEXT>
