<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / BTR to raise Pounds 66m by Canadian stake sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BTR, the industrial conglomerate, is to raise about Pounds 66m from the sale
of its 59 per cent stake in Hawker Siddeley Canada, as it continues to
refocus on its core industrial manufacturing businesses.
This follows the disposal in recent months of two wholesale and distribution
companies for a total of Pounds 245.5m, and the announcement of the
flotation of Graham Group on the London Stock Exchange.
Hawker Siddeley Canada, part of BTR's Pounds 1.55bn acquisition of the
Hawker Siddeley group in late 1991, is involved in businesses ranging from
industrial maintenance and transportation leasing to mining contracting and
some manufacturing.
BTR said the company no longer fitted into its strategy of focusing on pure
industrial manufacturing, currently accounting for about 85 per cent of
sales.
BTR owns 4.82m ordinary shares in Hawker Siddeley Canada, a Toronto-listed
company. The shares will be sold through a fully underwritten placement led
by RBC Dominion, at a price to be finalised shortly. Based on Monday's
closing price of CDollars 27, the placement will raise CDollars 130m.
Mr Alan Jackson, BTR's chief executive, said the Canadian subsidiary had
shareholders' funds of CDollars 240m and no borrowings, apart from
non-recourse debt from its leasing operations.
Analysts believe the latest sale should end an aggressive run of disposals,
which has left the group with a clearer structure and a stronger balance
sheet.
BTR had gearing estimated at 60 per cent in December 1993. With the cash
proceeds from the flotation of Graham Group, the sale of Hawker Siddeley
Canada and the exercise of 1993-1994 warrants, this figure could fall to
around 40 per cent this year. The management demonstrated its comfort with
current gearing levels in December through the purchase of US manufacturer
Rexnord for Dollars 420m (Pounds 283m) cash plus the assumption of Dollars
400m debt.
The group's share price closed 9 1/2 p higher at 374p.
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
