<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / British Gas issues first 50-year Eurobond
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British Gas yesterday issued the first ever 50-year Eurosterling bond,
taking advantage of low long-term UK interest rates.
The company's decision to issue extra-long bonds was motivated by its desire
to offer a novel investment vehicle to yield-hungry investors while securing
low funding costs for itself, according to Mr Arthur Burgess, British Gas's
treasurer.
'Long UK interest rates are around their lowest levels for the last 30 years
and we wanted to lock in those low rates for the long term,' said Mr
Burgess. He believes long-term rates are close to bottoming, and while UK
gilt yields may still slip further, 'issuing spreads (relative to gilt
yields) will probably widen out, so corporates won't be able to issue much
more cheaply than they can now'. He said the maturity was also chosen for
its novelty value. 'We could have tapped the 25 or 30-year sector, but we
preferred to go further out on the yield curve to distinguish ourselves from
competing paper,' he said.
The main buyers of the bonds were UK life insurance companies and pension
funds which like to match their long-term assets and liabilities. Some
overseas demand for the paper was also reported, with investors attracted by
the relatively high yields compared with government and corporate bonds in
other European markets, as well as scope for further sterling appreciation.
British Gas issued Pounds 200m of 7 1/8 per cent bonds maturing in February
2044 via CS First Boston. Buoyed by the gilt market rally, but also by
strong investor demand, the bonds ended the day at 99.40 bid, well above
their 98.74 re-offer price, yielding 49 basis points over the long gilt due
2017.
Many observers expect more long-dated bond issues in the near future. 'The
risk for borrowers is that, if they wait too long, they may miss an
opportunity to lock in low funding rates,' said a market analyst at a London
investment bank. Following the successful British Gas issue, he expects to
see 'a few more copycat issues from UK companies, though they have to be
very strong double-A rated names'. British Gas is rated AA2 by Moody's and
AA-plus by Standard &amp; Poor's.
Lex, Page 20; Capital markets, Page 29
</TEXT>
