<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
For once the waterfall of publicity preceding a new series is justified. The
Day Today is yet another example of Radio 4 serving as a forcing house for
television comedy. The radio series 'On The Hour' is wickedly funny because
it mocks other programes not for their content but their style. It does this
with such accuracy that the listeners' reaction programme, Feedback, has
received letters of complaint which assume 'On The Hour' is the real thing,
whatever the week's target: news, sport, religion and so on. Now producers
Armando Ianucci and Chris Morris and impressionist/comedian Steve Coogan
have brought the idea to television and tonight's targets include sports
round-ups and those ghastly 'video boobs' programmes (9.00 BBC2).
That is followed by Part 2 of Middlemarch in which Dorothea's marriage,
doomed from the outset, gets stickier, and young Dr Lydgate discovers his
enemies when he becomes head of the fever hospital (9.30 BBC2). Building
Sights USA at 8.50 on BBC2 features Frank Lloyd Wright's 'Ennis-Brown
House'.
</TEXT>
