<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Farmers seek new path to market: Deborah Hargreaves hears
why the potato board is under fire
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Graham Solari, a West Midlands farmer, lavishes tender loving care on the
3,000 tonnes of early potatoes he grows each year to ensure they attain high
standards. He takes equal pride in knowing what his customers want.
'We've spent two years talking to our customers: they want white potatoes
that look nice, are fresh and are the right shape,' he says.
Mr Solari describes his tubers as 'canting' potatoes, an old Black Country
expression. 'It means you can put the potatoes on to boil, hang out your
washing and cant to the neighbour for an hour, and when you're back the
potato is still boiling away and hasn't disintegrated.'
He is proud of his own marketing skills and is adamant he needs no
centralised body to do the job for him. He is one of at least 400 producers
who have signed a petition calling for an immediate end to Britain's Potato
Marketing Board.
Changes to the potato board, which has controlled production for 60 years,
were announced in November by Mrs Gillian Shephard, agriculture minister.
She said the board would be phased out over three years, but in the meantime
it would act as a central research and marketing agency.
But a growing number of farmers want the board abolished now. 'There's
nothing the board does for me that I can't do better myself,' says Mr
Solari, who pays Pounds 5,000 a year for membership out of his Pounds
320,000 turnover on potatoes.
The rebel growers have collected enough names in opposition to the board to
force it to hold a national poll on its future. They hope this will be held
within weeks.
Mr Solari thinks farmers should become closer to consumers themselves rather
than relying on a central agency to do it for them.
He says: 'There are a lot of smaller producers who think that, in some
magical way, the potato board will rescue them if they're inefficient.
That's just not going to happen.'
Mr Solari has this year's seed potatoes sitting in plastic trays in
insulated buildings on his 150 acres. Each stage of their growth is
carefully monitored.
Mr Solari uses 13 workers and a potato harvester to grade, sort and pack the
potatoes, en route, in the hope they remain as fresh as possible when they
arrive in the shops.
Last year he made a good profit but the drive for quality came after a loss
in 1992 when the market was oversupplied. 'We cut back our production by
1,000 tonnes to make sure we could concentrate more on quality,' he says.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
