<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Treasury to face critics from industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Senior Treasury officials are to meet 70 industrialists next month to answer
charges that they are too secretive and have become divorced from the
business community.
The private meeting has been arranged for the Treasury by the Whitehall and
Industry Group, a little-known charity funded by the government and 64 big
companies.
It comes as part of a broad effort by the Treasury to seek better contacts
with business people after criticism that it had made mistakes in economic
policy partly because it has not known enough about the world outside
Whitehall.
On the agenda will be ways of ensuring Treasury officials understand how
economic policies affect companies - for example in investment allowances
and efforts to attract private capital into government programmes. Senior
Treasury officials think this process can be achieved by more swapping of
staff between Whitehall and business.
The gathering at the Institution of Civil Engineers in London is being
billed as a no-holds-barred session in which participants will be asked to
speak bluntly.
Among those attending are Mr Robert Armitage, finance director of the UK
division of US drugs company Merck, Mr John Mayo, finance director of
Zeneca, Mr Keith Todd, ICL finance director, and Mr Clive Hopkins, finance
director of Shell UK. Other companies being represented include Marks and
Spencer, Kingfisher, IBM, British Petroleum, Royal Bank of Scotland, British
Aerospace, and Texaco.
The Treasury case will be put by a quartet of top officials led by Sir Terry
Burns, permanent secretary.
Mr Christopher Haskins, the chairman of Northern Foods, who has attacked the
Treasury as being cut off from industry, will give an address aimed at
pulling together criticism of the department.
Others to speak include Mr Stephen Dorrell, financial secretary to the
Treasury, Mr Rupert Pennant-Rea, deputy governor of the Bank of England, and
Mr John Watts, Tory chairman of the Commons Treasury and civil service
committee.
The other Treasury officials who have agreed to face a possibly hostile
audience include chief economic adviser Mr Alan Budd, and Mr Andrew Turnbull
and Mr Steve Robson, in charge of public spending and industry respectively.
</TEXT>
