FT  19 JAN 94 / Pay freezes may affect 2m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Nearly 2m employees may be covered by pay freezes, the Confederation of
British Industry says.
The CBI's latest Employment Affairs Report says its pay databank suggests
that a quarter of manufacturers and a sixth of service companies are
operating pay freezes.
The organisation also stresses that there is little sign of 'catching-up'
awards when freezes end. Settlements after a pay standstill, at 2.1 per cent
in the private sector, compare with an average of 3.4 per cent for all
settlements last year.
The CBI cites several cases - including a distributor and retailer in the
south-east with a turnover of Pounds 100m and 1,200 employees. The
distributor had to cut costs as trade dwindled, and introduced a 12-month
wage freeze.
The CBI said: 'The freeze was followed by a 1.5 per cent award but there was
no element of catch-up.' Job vacancies at executive level rose sharply in
the fourth quarter of last year, according to the latest jobs survey by MSL,
the recruitment consultants. Recruitment for high-technology jobs was up by
142 per cent compared with the fourth quarter of 1992, while there was
growth of 156 per cent in retailing management jobs.
</TEXT>
