<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Shop crime hits morale and profit: 1.2m customers and 28,000
staff detained in connection with offences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Retailers' profits would have been 23 per cent higher last year without the
growing problem of retail crime, the British Retail Consortium said
yesterday.
The consortium, which represents 90 per cent of UK retailers, said its first
comprehensive survey of retail crime revealed that the true cost of crime to
retailers was about Pounds 2bn a year.
That was more than the cost of running the magistrates' courts system for a
year, and almost twice the annual cost of running the Crown Prosecution
Service.
The survey found a total of 2.1m criminal incidents in the retail industry
including 1.5m customer thefts. The consortium warned that 'small retailers'
profitability and morale can often be so affected by crime that continued
trading is no longer viable'.
The 120,000 incidents of criminal damage - or 54 for every 100 shops -
compares with only eight in 100 individuals who have their cars vandalised
each year, and seven in 100 whose homes are vandalised.
The survey's other main findings included:
Almost 3,700 arson attacks.
More than 14,400 robberies.
More than 31,000 incidents of theft or fraud by staff. Pounds 21.7m losses
to retailers through fraud using payment cards, cheque cards and other
means.
More than 7,000 incidents of terrorism, including confirmed incidents and
hoaxes.
Incidence of burglary was highest for grocery stores (95 per 100 stores).
Retailers detained 1.2m customers and 28,000 staff in connection with
crimes, but dealt with 450,000 of these themselves, without passing them on
to the police.
Many retailers do not bother to hand over shoplifters because of the slim
chance of a conviction under the present system. But the consortium said the
answer was not necessarily tougher laws or a clampdown on shoplifters.
'If every shop thief was handed over to the police, the whole criminal
justice system would grind to a halt,' said Mr James Mays, director-general.
He added that there were ways in which retailers could improve their
co-operation with the Crown Prosecution Service to increase the arrest rate
of persistent and professional shoplifters, and make sure they were
'prosecuted to the full extent of the law'.
Retail Crime Costs. British Retail Consortium, Bedford House, 69/79 Fulham
High Street, London SW6 3JW. Pounds 20.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
                  RETAILERS COUNT THE COST OF CRIME
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Survey findings:
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Retail profits would have been 23 per cent higher were it not for the
cost of crime
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
For every ten shops there were six burglaries, eight times the burglary
risk to the average household
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Six in very 100 premises experienced robbery
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
37 per cent of customers suspected of crime and 44 per cent of staff
suspects were dealt with by retailers themselves
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
The total number of suspects were dealt with internally - and whose
cases did not come to court - was 450,000
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Some 14,000 staff were subjected to violence and there were 106,000
threats of violence
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
