<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Building society returns to pension transfers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Yorkshire Building Society is re-entering the pension transfers market with
a service offering customers independent actuarial advice.
The new service, which will be available from the end of this month, comes
against a background of widespread failure across the financial services
industry to comply with regulatory requirements in cases where people
transferred savings out of occupational pensions schemes into private plans.
A study by accountants KPMG Peat Marwick for the Securities and Investments
Board, the City's chief watchdog, found that regulatory guidelines were
breached in nine out of 10 pension transfer cases.
Yorkshire's service will link the society with Buck Consultants, an
independent firm of actuaries.
Under the arrangement, which has been worked out over the past six months or
so, Yorkshire will make the initial contact with a customer and will then
take him or her through a questionnaire.
For a flat fee of Pounds 75, Buck will then assess the benefits from the
occupational scheme and the investment returns required for higher benefits.
It will then prepare an actuarial report to go to both customer and building
society. This will include a statement recommending whether the customer
should take the transfer value or not. If the advice is to transfer out of
the scheme into a personal plan, Yorkshire, which is one of the few larger
societies to act as an independent financial adviser, would hope to advise
the customer.
Their usual fee for a similar service would be about Pounds 150, Buck said.
Mr Derek Roberts, Yorkshire chief executive, said yesterday that the society
hoped 'to bring some order to the marketplace'. He believes that people are
more likely to trust advice from a society than from elsewhere in the
financial services industry.
Yorkshire, the 12th-largest society in the UK, has given financial advice to
around 50,000 customers, but has only 300 pension transfer cases. Its
customer base is about 1m. It stopped writing pensions transfer business
early last year.
Yorkshire decided to re-enter the market because the question of what to do
with a pension from previous employment loomed so large in its discussions
with customers about personal pensions.
One of the issues thrown up by the inquiry into pension transfers has been
that sales agents and advisers seek enough information about the
occupational scheme, on issues such as discretionary benefits, to ensure
that they can give proper advice on whether a customer should take a
transfer.
</TEXT>
