<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Cleveland to be replaced by four unitary councils
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Cleveland County Council is to be abolished and replaced by four all-purpose
unitary authorities, Mr John Gummer, environment secretary, announced
yesterday.
Local businesses reacted furiously to the move, which is the first formal
decision to be made by the government on restructuring a mainland county
since the review of English local government structure was announced by Mr
Michael Heseltine, then environment secretary, in 1991.
Mr Gummer said the new structure would 'bring the benefits of unitary local
authorities to Cleveland: better service delivery, more efficient and
effective local government and - most importantly - one door to knock on,
making the council as accountable as possible to local people'.
Sir Ian Wrigglesworth, northern region chairman of the Confederation of
British Industry, said: 'Businesses won't have to knock on one door, but on
three council doors in the Teesside conurbation, and the doors of quite a
number of joint organisations which will run services across the whole
Teesside area.'
Ratepayers, he said, would have to pay the bill for a less efficient system
than could have been put in place. The CBI has lobbied for three districts
to be merged to form a Teesside unitary council, with Hartlepool left as an
independent unitary authority.
The leaders of all three political parties on Cleveland County Council
renewed their call for Teessiders to 'rise up in protest' at an 'impending
disaster'. The announcement was welcomed by the four Cleveland district
councils.
The option chosen by Mr Gummer is in line with the recommendation by Sir
John Banham, chairman of the Local Government Commission.
Cleveland County Council has already applied for judicial review of Sir
John's recommendations, claiming they are 'ill-considered, unwanted and
expensive'.
</TEXT>
