<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Cabinet briefed on de-regulation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
No fewer than 14 cabinet ministers are to attend a de-regulation seminar at
Downing Street this morning in a meeting that should assure the government's
de-regulation bill of a high-profile send-off.
The bill, to be published today, has been flagged as one of the main
elements of a legislative programme designed to unite the Conservative party
after last year's Maastricht-related traumas.
Downing Street said last night that the high turnout of cabinet heavyweights
 -headed by Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Michael Heseltine,
trade and industry secretary - expected at today's meeting reflected the
'great importance' the government attached to de-regulation.
The bill, which will run to just under 100 clauses, is expected to give the
Department of Trade and Industry sweeping powers to repeal hundreds of
regulatory measures without primary legislation.
This has already led to controversy, with Mr Heseltine forced to reassure
MPs that the measures would not undermine parliament's authority.
There is expected to be provision for establishing some form of scrutiny
procedure, probably by MPs. The DTI has said there are no plans to 'avoid
public scrutiny' through the use of orders in crown procedures.
Today's meeting, to be chaired by Mr John Major, the prime minister, will
also be attended by the chairmen of the eight business task forces charged
with identifying regulations that could be scrapped after the contents of
the bill are published.
Treasury to face critics, Page 8
</TEXT>
