<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Imro registration system changes
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Imro, the self-regulating body for the fund management industry, yesterday
issued a consultation document proposing rules that require individuals
employed by member firms to register individually with it.
The system is aimed at identifying individuals who are either incompetent or
who have been dismissed by their employer for wrongdoing, and preventing
them from finding employment with another firm. 'Imro believes that
investors will be better protected against wrongdoing and incompetence and
that members too will benefit through the identification and, where
necessary, removal of individuals who cannot meet the required standards,'
the body said.
The document, which invites comment by February 25, describes the mechanisms
by which individual registration will be introduced and the changes needed.
Imro said it was 'aware of the need to avoid unnecessary bureaucracy and
costs and will introduce the system with the minimum amount of complexity
and paperwork'.
</TEXT>
