<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Financial watchdog is unruffled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The board of the Personal Investment Authority, the proposed new watchdog
for retail financial services, yesterday underlined its determination to
press ahead with the corporate governance plans that last week prompted one
of its directors to resign.
After a meeting at which it discussed the planned budget for its first year,
the board also appeared likely to retain the systems of existing bodies for
deciding what membership fees organisations should pay, instead of creating
a new basis for calculating subscriptions.
Estimates of the first-year costs are around Pounds 30m. This would suggest
higher subscription fees than those paid to existing regulators.
The PIA took the opportunity of announcing the appointment of two more
public interest directors, Sir John Bailey and Sir Terry Heiser. This
confirms that the 19-strong board will contain only nine people currently
practising within the industry, as had been planned.
It was this decision that led to the resignation from the proposed authority
of Mr Jim Stretton, deputy managing director of Standard Life, and the
statement from Standard Life that it withdrew its support from the PIA and
would favour statutory regulation.
Sir John Bailey, a former Treasury solicitor, is a director of Lautro, the
self-regulatory organisation for the life assurance industry. He chairs the
inquiry into the auditing of the collapsed Bank of Credit and Commerce
International.
Sir Terry Heiser, a former permanent secretary of the environment
department, holds a number of non-executive directorships, including Abbey
National and Smith New Court.
Two more public interest directors have still to be recruited.
Yesterday's meeting also agreed proposals on monitoring, enforcement and
acceptance by the new regulator, which is due to come into force around the
middle of the year. The board will meet next week to discuss a draft of the
PIA prospectus.
The prospectus, to be published next month, must be approved by the
Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, in order for
the PIA to be recognised as a regulator.
Society resumes advice, Page 8
</TEXT>
