<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Japan adopts public works bidding plan
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Japanese government yesterday adopted a long-awaited programme to
increase the transparency of the country's bidding system for public works
projects and improve access to the market for foreign contractors.
The move, which is expected to help avert sanctions by the US against Japan
for its failure to open its public works market to foreign companies, comes
just two days before a US deadline for a decision on whether to impose
sanctions against Japan.
Mr Morihiro Hosokawa, Japanese prime minister, hailed the measure as
introducing an 'historic' change in Japan's public sector works. Mr Tsutomu
Hata, foreign minister, called on his fellow ministers to support the
implementation of the measures which he said were 'internationally
appropriate' and in line with the agreement reached in the Uruguay Round of
trade talks.
Despite official enthusiasm, the plan is widely regarded in Japan as
insufficient to change the close relationships between Japanese construction
companies and public sector institutions and the collusive and exclusive
business practices that characterise the country's construction market.
It is unclear whether the programme will be seen as adequate in Washington.
A US trade official said yesterday that the plan was being reviewed by an
inter-agency committee which will make its views known tomorrow, the
sanctions deadline.
The plan, to be implemented in April, calls for the adoption of an open and
competitive bidding system for public works projects sponsored by the
central government and public corporations which are valued at SDR4.5m
(special drawing rights) - Pounds 41.53m - and for those sponsored by
prefectures and specified cities which are valued at more than SDR15m.
For design and consulting services, the area of most interest to foreign
firms, the thresholds above which an open bidding system will be the rule
are SDR450,000 for central government projects and SDR1.5m for prefectural
governments.
More transparent guidelines on public tendering are to be drawn up by
Japan's Fair Trade Commission and the experience of foreign companies
outside Japan will be taken into account in evaluating the eligibility of
foreign companies to bid for projects.
Under Japan's present system, only companies which have been designated by
the projects' sponsors are eligible to bid for a contract.
Penalties against unfair practices will also be strengthened in response to
criticism that past penalties have been too weak. Japan and the US will
continue to assess progress by foreign companies in winning public works
contracts.
The plan opens a substantial proportion of Japanese public works projects to
open bidding.
Widespread implementation of the new measures will depend to a large extent
on the size of the penalties against illicit practices which will be decided
later this year.
</TEXT>
