<HEADLINE>
FT  19 JAN 94 / Russians to stay in Baltics, says Kozyrev
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN LLOYD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Andrei Kozyrev, the Russian foreign minister, indicated yesterday that
Russian troops would stay in the Baltics in spite of commitments, repeated
at the US-Russian summit last week, to withdraw them as soon as possible.
Mr Kozyrev told a conference on Russian policy towards the countries of the
Commonwealth of Independent States and the Baltic states that complete
withdrawal of troops 'from this region' would be against Russia's interests
 -because it would create a security vacuum and because it would leave
ethnic Russians undefended. Both Tass and Interfax news agencies indicated
that Mr Kozyrev had included the Baltic countries in his remarks on the
troop pull-out.
'We should not withdraw from these regions which have been in the sphere of
Russian interests for centuries and we should not fear these words,' Tass
quoted him as saying.
In Washington, a State Department spokesman said clarification might be
sought as the remarks were at odds with statements by President Boris
Yeltsin during President Bill Clinton's recent visit to Moscow.
The remarks, if confirmed as applying to the Baltic states of Estonia and
Latvia (Russian troops have already left Lithuania), will stir alarm in
those countries. They have long warned that Russian commitments to pull out
troops were hostage to political shifts in Moscow. The remarks are
surprising from a liberal minister like Mr Kozyrev.
In identifying the protection of ethnic Russians in the former Soviet states
as 'one of Moscow's main strategic interests', he is stealing some of the
rhetoric of Mr Vladimir Zhirinovsky's Liberal Democratic party and
delivering a pointed warning to Estonia and Latvia, where citizenship laws
have withheld voting rights from non-ethnic Balts until language and other
criteria are met.
Russia has military bases in all former Soviet states except Lithuania and
Azerbaijan. Areas of tension apart from the Baltics include Moldova, where
the 14th Army under General Lebed guards the Russian-speaking population in
the Trans Dnestr region, and Ukraine, where ownership of the Black Sea fleet
in its Crimean bases is in contention between Russia and Ukraine - a
contention which would be increased by the election of a president of Crimea
who favours union with Russia, as now seems likely.
</TEXT>
