<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / International Company News: Alcan blames glut for losses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MONTREAL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Alcan Aluminium, one of the world's biggest aluminium producers, blamed the
world aluminium glut for a fourth-quarter loss of USDollars 36m, or 17 cents
a share, including a rationalisation charge of USDollars 25m.
This compared with a Dollars 56m loss equal to 29 cents a share in the 1992
quarter, including Dollars 49m of special charges. Revenues in the latest
quarter were Dollars 1.8bn, down slightly.
Alcan's loss for all 1993 was Dollars 104m, or 54 cents a share, against a
loss of Dollars 112m, or 60 cents. Special charges were Dollars 37m against
Dollars 58m. Revenues were down slightly at Dollars 7.23bn.
Mr Jacques Bougie, president, blamed massive CIS exports for creating the
overcapacity crisis. LME spot ingot prices touched a new low (after
inflation) of 46 US cents per pound in December. The price has since risen
to 54.5 US cents yesterday on hopes of an international agreement on global
production cutbacks.
Alcan last week decided to close temporarily another 156,000 tonnes of ingot
capacity in north America, Brazil and Britain.
Fabricated product volumes hit new highs in the fourth quarter and 1993, but
prices fell through the year. Ingot shipments were lower in the fourth
quarter but higher for the year, but prices weakened.
But Alcan's operating results benefited from cost reductions and lower
interest costs. The year-to-year losses were reduced in Canada, Latin
America and the Pacific area, but were higher in the US, Europe and
elsewhere.
</TEXT>
