<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / International Company News: Falling debt lifts Union Carbide
in final quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Fourth-quarter profits at Union Carbide were comfortably ahead of market
expectations, thanks to falling debt and the effects of cost-cutting, the US
chemicals group said.
Although its full results will not be released until the middle of next
week, the company said earnings per share for the period would be about 25
cents, higher than most market estimates. It earned 23 cents a share in the
previous three months, and 12 cents a share in the fourth quarter of 1992.
Union Carbide said margins for some of its major products were lower than a
year earlier, reflecting the continuing overcapacity in the chemicals
industry. However, earnings were higher due to lower fixed costs and
interest expense.
The company has been pushing through a cost reduction programme designed to
save around Dollars 400m a year, and had previously projected interest costs
last year of around Dollars 75m, down from Dollars 140m in 1991.
