<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / International Company News: Alexander &amp; Alexander in moves
to replace chief
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Non-executive directors of Alexander &amp; Alexander have acted to replace Mr
Tinsley Irvin, the US insurance brokers' long-time chairman and chief
executive, after a succession of mishaps and disappointing results at the
group.
Mr Irvin has stepped down immediately as chairman and will be replaced as
chief executive once a replacement from outside the group has been found.
The move follows a special board meeting on Friday to consider the
management of the group.
Mr Irvin said he and the board had agreed that 'significant changes in
leadership' were necessary 'in order to accelerate the pace of change and
effect improvements in operations and earnings.'
He added: 'Some of the old ways we do business must also change.'
Two months ago, Alexander &amp; Alexander, the world's second-largest insurance
broker after Marsh &amp; McLennan, restated earnings back to 1991 when it
discovered that its Alexander Consulting Group arm had been overstating its
revenues.
Earlier last year, the group had to take a special Dollars 157.5m charge to
cover indemnity costs related mainly to a business it had sold some years
previously.
Mr Robert Boni, a former chairman of Armco, the steel company, has taken
over as chairman and will head a committee of non-executive directors
charged with finding a new chief executive for the group.
Efforts would be made to lift the company's revenues, cut its costs and
improve organisation controls, Mr Boni said. He paid tribute to the
accomplishments Mr Irvin had achieved, adding that he had brought the
company through a turbulent period.
Mr Irvin became chief executive in 1987, as the US broker was recovering
from fraud losses it suffered in Alexander Howden, the Lloyd's insurance
broker it had acquired in 1982. He became chairman a year later.
The company said it would divide these two roles in the future.
Alexander &amp; Alexander has suffered from flagging profits in its large US
retail insurance broking operations, as well as from a disappointing record
from its international acquisitions. These include Alexander Howden and, in
1985, Canadian broker Reed Stenhouse. Mr Irvin, 60, had been with the
company since 1953, and will remain a director.
</TEXT>
