<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / International Company News: Commerzbank links with
Winterthur
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WINTERTHUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Winterthur Insurance is to take control of DBV Versicherung from
Commerzbank, a move which will make the Swiss group the 10th largest primary
insurer in Germany by premium income.
Winterthur, which has been seeking for several years to build up a
substantial presence in Germany, will pay Commerzbank a combination of cash
and shares for a 75 per cent interest in the holding company which has a
50.1 per cent stake in DBV. Winterthur will also transfer its own German
insurance businesses to the holding.
Mr Peter Spalti, Winterthur chairman, said that no offer would be made to
the minority shareholders of DBV, as there would be no change in the direct
ownership of the Frankfurt-quoted group.
Commerzbank will retain a minority 25 per cent in the enlarged holding. Both
it and DBV-Winterthur will exploit each other's sales networks for banking
and insurance products.
Mr Spalti said that the takeover would transform Winterthur, the Swiss
market leader, into a truly European group.
The company already has a substantial stake in the UK through its Churchill
motor insurance subsidiary and Provident Life, but earns less than a 10th of
its premium income in Germany.
The combined 1993 premium income of DBV and Winterthur's German operations
was about DM4.9bn (Dollars 2.8bn).
Nearly 60 per cent of DBV's DM3.4bn premium income last year came from life
insurance; 27 per cent from health insurance; and the rest from non-life
insurance.
Winterthur's subsidiaries in Germany earned DM1.5bn in premiums, some
two-thirds of which from non-life business.
Mr Manfred Broska, chief executive of DBV, will continue to lead the
enlarged group. Mr Broska said that the German insurance market was going
through a difficult period, because of recession and liberalisation.
However, he said he was confident that DBV, with its connections with
Commerzbank and Winterthur, was well placed to succeed.
Mr Broska said that the group expected to achieve a satisfactory result for
1993 and that there was room for another dividend increase. In 1992, it had
net income of DM32.6m and paid a dividend of DM8 per share.
Mr Spalti said Commerzbank would acquire a less than 5 per cent stake in
Winterthur as a result of the takeover and that Mr Martin Kohlhaussen,
Commerzbank's chairman, would join the Winterthur board.
</TEXT>
