<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / The Lex Column: Eastern Electricity
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Eastern Electricity's decision to buy up to 5 per cent of its shares is a
small but significant admission of the regional companies' embarrassing
riches. The RECs are heading rapidly towards net cash, and even a harsh
review of their price caps is unlikely to stop cash generation completely.
Funding utilities with equity alone is expensive. While share buy backs
help, a much more radical restructuring is needed to get the RECs back on to
a sensible footing. Interestingly, the regulator cited cost of capital as an
issue he will consider in his current price review. If the RECs do not
produce plans to gear up, return excess funds to shareholders and cut bills
to customers, the regulator may do it for them.
</TEXT>
