<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JAN 94 / Business and the Law: Monopoly threat - Legal Briefs
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
UK solicitors' monopoly on the conduct of litigation is under threat from a
new professional body aiming to corner a share of the construction
litigation market. The Institute of Commercial Litigators was formed by five
international firms of construction consultants that already handle
arbitration work - James R. Knowles, Cyril Sweett, Bucknall Austin, Beard
Dove and Tweeds. The institute has applied to the Lord Chancellor's Advisory
Committee for the right of its members to conduct litigation. It plans to
offer clients a faster, cheaper service undercutting solicitors' fees by up
to 50 per cent.
Institute director Patrick Lineen said: 'There is little difference between
complex arbitration and complex litigation.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
